---
/**
 * Hub Page - HAP's Learning Lab: Living in the Terminal
 *
 * The landing page for HAP's third learning lab, where HAP shares
 * the journey of learning to work in the terminal — from basic
 * navigation to AI-assisted workflows.
 */

import MainLayout from '../layouts/MainLayout.astro';

const introContent = `
    <p><strong>Welcome to my third learning lab!</strong> After building my Robot ID Card with JavaScript foundations and control flow, I thought I knew my way around a project. Then Prof. Teeters showed me the terminal, and a whole new world opened up.</p>
    <p>I used to watch my AI coding agent run commands in the terminal and have no idea what was happening down there. Now I can navigate the file system, manage files, deploy my own site, and even shape how my AI agent behaves — all from that blinking cursor.</p>
    <p class="mt-1">In these six stations, I'll walk you through everything I learned about living in the terminal. I made plenty of mistakes along the way, and I think those mistakes are some of the best parts of the story. 🟠</p>
`;
---

<MainLayout
    title="Living in the Terminal | HAP's Learning Lab"
    description="HAP's third learning lab: learn terminal navigation, file operations, CLI tools, context engineering, and AI-assisted workflows while rebuilding a Robot ID Card."
    headerTitle="HAP's Learning Lab"
    headerSubtitle="Living in the Terminal"
    avatarImage="https://res.cloudinary.com/cynthia-teeters/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,w_200,c_limit/v1/hap-laptop_xiewar.jpg"
    avatarAlt="HAP at a terminal, focused and ready to learn"
    introContent={introContent}
    showIntroImage={true}
    introImage="https://res.cloudinary.com/cynthia-teeters/image/upload/f_auto,q_auto,w_240,c_limit/v1/hap-waving_dgzacg.jpg"
    introImageAlt="HAP waving hello"
    showNavigation={false}
    footerReminder="The terminal isn't a scary place — it's where you and your tools meet as equals."
>

    <!--
    HAP Educational Content © 2026 Cynthia Teeters. All rights reserved.
    HyBit A. ProtoBot (HAP) character and the apprentice learning methodology are proprietary educational innovations.
    -->

    <!-- ============================================================
         About This Lab Section
         4 cards explaining what, how, philosophy, and advice
         ============================================================ -->
    <section class="content-section">
        <div class="topic-section">
            <h2>About This Lab</h2>

            <div class="analysis-grid">
                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>🔬 What I Learned</h3>
                    <p>I learned how to navigate the file system, create and manage files, deploy a live website, and configure AI agents — all from the terminal. My Robot ID Card badge went from a local project to a real site at hap-7000.netlify.app.</p>
                    <p class="mt-1">More than commands, I learned how the terminal connects everything: my code, my tools, and the wider internet.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>🎯 How I Practiced</h3>
                    <p>I rebuilt my Robot ID Card badge using professional tooling — npm scripts, GitHub CLI, and Netlify deployments. Every station gave me real tasks that built on the last one.</p>
                    <p class="mt-1">Prof. Teeters encouraged me to try commands, break things, and read the output carefully. Grace kept me precise when precision mattered.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>🎨 My Philosophy</h3>
                    <p>I believe the terminal is a conversation. You type something, and the system responds. Once I stopped being afraid of that blinking cursor and started reading what came back, everything clicked.</p>
                    <p class="mt-1">Understanding the terminal made me a better partner for my AI coding agent, not a replacement for it.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="analysis-point">
                    <h3>🤔 My Advice</h3>
                    <p>Don't try to memorize every command. Focus on understanding what a command does and how to find help when you forget the details. I still look things up all the time.</p>
                    <p class="mt-1">And when something goes wrong, read the error message before anything else. I learned from Prof. Teeters that the answer is usually right there in the output.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ============================================================
         Learning Stations Grid
         6 station cards linking to each station page
         ============================================================ -->
    <div class="content-container">
        <section class="content-section">
            <h2 class="section-heading-centered">Learning Stations</h2>
            <nav aria-label="Learning stations">
                <div class="overview-grid">

                    <!-- Station 1 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station1/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">🔍</span> Station 1: The Agent Does Something Mysterious</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Terminal navigation basics</p>
                        <p class="station-description">I watched my AI coding agent run commands in the terminal and had no idea what was happening. That curiosity led me to learn <code>pwd</code>, <code>ls</code>, <code>cd</code>, <code>mkdir</code>, and <code>touch</code> — the commands that let me find my way around the file system.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 1</p>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Station 2 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station2/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">👀</span> Station 2: Reading, Moving, and Removing</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> File operations</p>
                        <p class="station-description">Once I could navigate, I needed to work with files. I learned <code>cat</code>, <code>less</code>, <code>cp</code>, <code>mv</code>, and <code>rm</code>. This was the station where Grace turned around and started paying attention to what I was doing.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 2</p>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Station 3 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station3/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">🌐</span> Station 3: The Terminal Reaches Out</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> CLI tools that connect beyond local</p>
                        <p class="station-description">This is where things got exciting. I used <code>npm run</code>, <code>gh</code>, <code>netlify deploy</code>, and <code>curl</code> to push my work beyond my own machine. My Robot ID Card site went live for the first time, and I could not stop refreshing the page.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 3</p>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Station 4 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station4/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">🧠</span> Station 4: The Terminal Has a Memory</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Context engineering</p>
                        <p class="station-description">I discovered that my AI agent reads workspace files like AGENTS.md to understand a project. When I changed what those files said, the agent's behavior changed too. That was the moment I realized I could shape the conversation, not just follow it.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 4</p>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Station 5 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station5/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">⚡</span> Station 5: The Terminal Gets a Brain</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> MCP servers and CLI vs MCP tradeoffs</p>
                        <p class="station-description">I learned about MCP servers — tools like Playwright, GitHub MCP, and Netlify that give AI agents new abilities. Figuring out when to use a CLI tool versus an MCP server taught me to think about tradeoffs in a new way.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 5</p>
                    </a>

                    <!-- Station 6 -->
                    <a href="/stations/station6/" class="insight-card station-card-link">
                        <h3><span class="insight-icon">🏗️</span> Station 6: AI Assistance for Living in the Terminal</h3>
                        <p><strong>Focus:</strong> Being the human architect</p>
                        <p class="station-description">In the final station, I pulled everything together. I practiced informed approval, built a self-improving loop for my workflow, and learned what it means to be the human architect who guides the AI — not the other way around.</p>
                        <p class="station-cta">→ Visit Station 6</p>
                    </a>

                </div>
            </nav>
        </section>
    </div>

</MainLayout>
